Another recipe I love and another that makes me scratch my head at those who've had problems. This is insanely easy to make, has a great blend of flavors, and is one of my easy favorites; I've made this at least 10 times over the last 2 years. My tips: - I leave the skin on; more fat, but it crisps up great and really adds to the flavor. If you leave it on, cook it well to begin with (deep brown on both sides), so you don't have to heat it too long in sauce where the skin could get soft. - I've used both yellow and smooth dijon mustards; nothing fancy, both store brands (Kroger). - Turn the heat to med-hi/hi when reducing the sauce and let it boil; it will take about 5-10 minutes. - You may want to increase the quantity of sauce, maybe make 25-50% extra

