Rating: 4
I thought this was GREAT! I'm not an orange lover in cooking, so I was a bit concerned that the orange would be overwhelming, but decided to go forth! I had 6 thighs, so I increased the broth and the OJ to 1 cup each. I increased the mustard to about 1/2 cup. I stuck with a scant tablespoon of honey b/c I was worried about it being too sweet from the OJ. I used 2 tsp of Ass Kickin' Hot Sauce (I don't like the flavor of this sauce by itself, but it was fine to add the heat, and it's what I had in the cupboard.) I made sure to brown the thighs really well, so there were lots of brown bits in the pan to deglaze. I think this helped the sauce to thicken. I also added a couple of garlic cloves to the browning step. I had no trouble thickening the sauce after bringing it to a pretty robust boil. I served it with jasmine rice tossed with scallions. If I had them on hand, I would have also served some snow peas on the side. Although this dish is Creole, it seems to also have an Asian flair to my taste. I think it's the grainy mustard that makes this dish, plus the hot sauce, with a bit of sweetness to balance it all. I saw some reviewers cut back on the mustard to 2 tsp; I can only say it would be a very different dish. Perhaps increasing the mustard as I did also changed it significantly...but I'll do it again this way b/c it was terrific and there were no leftovers!

